@node Building
@section Building
@cindex Building

@noindent
When you have built and configured all libraries you must either set
@var{ADA_INCLUDE_PATH} and @var{ADA_OBJECTS_PATH} (for @code{GNAT}) to
point to the right directories or update the @var{ADASOCKETS},
@var{XMLADA} and @var{INSTALL} variables in the top
@file{makefile.conf}. You should have a look at file @file{INSTALL}
for installation instructions.

@noindent
At this point you can build @code{AWS} with:

@smallexample
@cartouche
@group
$ make build
@end group
@end cartouche
@end smallexample

@noindent
Note that by default @code{AWS} demos will be built without @code{SSL}
support except on Windows. If you want to build the demos with
@code{SSL} on UNIX (in this case you must have @file{libssl.a} and
@file{libcrypto.a} available on your platform), open
@file{makefile.conf} and set the @var{MODE} variable to ssl. Then
rebuild with:
@cindex libssl.a
@cindex libcrypto.a

@smallexample
@cartouche
@group
$ make build
@end group
@end cartouche
@end smallexample

@noindent
What is important to understand is that @code{AWS SSL} support is
selected at @b{link time} and not at configure time.

@noindent
It is is possible to build @code{AWS} in debug mode by setting
@var{DEBUG} make's variable in @file{makefile.conf}, or just:

@smallexample
@cartouche
@group
$ make build DEBUG=1
@end group
@end cartouche
@end smallexample

@noindent
Others make's targets are:

@table @code

@item build_lib

Build AWS library only.

@item build_tools

Build AWS tools only.

@item build_demos

Build AWS demos only.

@end table

@noindent
For example, if you use @code{GNAT} and want to use the @code{GNAT.Sockets}
implementation, you can build and install AWS with (you do not need to
edit the makefile.conf):

@smallexample
@cartouche
@group
$ make build
$ make install INSTALL=/opt
@end group
@end cartouche
@end smallexample

@c ----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node Demos
@section Demos

@noindent
During the build, the @code{AWS} library and demos will be compiled. The
demos are a good way to learn how to use @code{AWS}. Yet to learn all
features in @code{AWS} you'll need to read the documentation.

@noindent
Here are a short description of the demos:

@table @file

@item agent

A program using the AWS client interface. This simple tool can be used
to retrieve Web page content. It supports passing through a proxy with
authentication and basic authentication on the Web site.

@item auth

A simple program to test the Web Basic and Digest authentication feature.

@item com_1
@item com_2

Two simples program that uses the AWS communication service.

@item dispatch

A simple demo using the dispatcher facility. @pxref{URI dispatcher}.

@item hello_world

The famous Hello World program. This is a server that will always
return a Web page saying ``Hello World!''.

@item main
@item hotplug

A simple test for the hotplug feature.

@item res_demo

A demo using the resource feature. This Web Server embedded a @code{PNG}
image and an @code{HTML} page. The executable is self contained.

@item runme

A complete example that test many @code{AWS} features. If this test runs fine
on your platform, @code{AWS} is certainly ok.

@item split

A demo for the transient pages and page splitter AWS's feature. Here a
very big table is split on multiple pages. A set of links can be used
to navigate to the next or previous page or to access directly to a
given page.

@item test_jabber

A simple Jabber command line client to check the presence of a JID
(Jabber ID). This uses the Jabber API, @pxref{AWS.Jabber}.

@item test_ldap

A simple LDAP demo which access a public LDAP server and display some
information.

@item text_input

A simple demo which handle textarea and display the content.

@item vh_demo

Two servers on the same machine... virtual hosting demo.
@pxref{Virtual host dispatcher}.

@item web_mail

A simple Web Mail implementation that works on a POP mailbox.

@item ws

A static Web page server and push enabled server.

@item wps

A very simple static Web page server based on @code{AWS.Services.Page_Server}. 
@pxref{Static Page server}.

@item zdemo

A simple demo of the Gzip content encoding feature.

@end table

@noindent
If @code{XMLAda} is installed it is possible to build the @code{SOAP} binding
and the @code{SOAP} demos, for this just type:

@smallexample
@cartouche
@group
$ make build_soap
@end group
@end cartouche
@end smallexample

@noindent
There is four demos:

@table @file

@item soap_client
@item soap_server

A simple client/server program to test the @code{SOAP} protocol.

@item soap_svs

A server that implements the seven @code{SOAP} procedures for the validation
suite on @url{http://validator.soapware.org/}. This demo can be used
to validate @code{AWS/SOAP} on your platform.

@item soap_cvs

The client @code{SOAP} program that test all seven @code{SOAP}
procedure of the above server.

@end table

@noindent
In each case you'll certainly have to edit the makefile to correctly set
the include path for the libraries @code{POSIX}, @code{OpenSSL}, 
@code{Socket} and @code{XMLAda}. For more information, look at the makefiles.

@c ----------------------------------------------------------------------

@node Installing
@section Installing
@cindex Installing

@noindent
When the build is done you must install @code{AWS} at a specific
location. The target directory is defined with the @var{INSTALL}
@file{makefile.conf} variable. The default value is your home directory. To
install:

@smallexample
@cartouche
@group
$ make install
@end group
@end cartouche
@end smallexample

@noindent
To install @code{AWS} into another directory you can either edit
@file{makefile.conf} and set @var{INSTALL} to the directory you like
to install @code{AWS} or just force the make @code{INSTALL} variable:

@smallexample
@cartouche
@group
$ make install INSTALL=/opt
@end group
@end cartouche
@end smallexample

@noindent
Now you are ready to use @code{AWS} !

